        <h2>WHAT SUPERDEBATE IS</h2>

        <p>
            SuperDebate is the modern Agora—a network of debate clubs where adults gather to argue about ideas that matter. Not Twitter threads that spiral into insults. Not dinner conversations where someone changes the subject when things get interesting. Structured, timed, judged debate with clear rules and genuine stakes.
        </p>

        <p>
            A typical event runs three hours. You'll participate in up to six structured rounds, each with its own topic, opponent, and outcome. Between rounds, you rotate—new partner, new opponent, new challenge. The variety is the point. You can't rely on one style when you're facing six different people with six different approaches.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>The format is modular.</strong> SuperDebate isn't locked into a single structure. Some rounds might follow the full 28-minute format detailed in the <a href="/superdebate-format/">Format Guide</a>—constructive speeches, cross-examination, rebuttals. Others might be shorter, faster, more focused. The club adapts to its members and the evening's energy. This means you need to be adaptable too.
        </p>

        <div class="vocabulary-box">
            <span class="vocab-term">Flow</span>
            <span class="vocab-pronunciation">FLOW</span>
            <p class="vocab-definition">The debater's method for tracking arguments in real time. You create columns on paper: your case, their response, your extension, their rebuttal. Skilled debaters flow automatically, building a map of the debate as it unfolds. Without a flow, you're trusting memory under pressure—a losing bet.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
            <strong>You choose your participation style.</strong> Every attendee can debate solo or as part of a two-person team. Solo means you carry the full weight—every speech, every cross-examination, every rebuttal. Team means coordination: who takes constructive, who handles cross-ex, how you signal each other when something goes wrong. Different skills, different pressures. Try both.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Topics emerge from the room.</strong> Unlike tournaments with pre-announced resolutions, SuperDebate topics come from attendees. People submit possibilities—political theory, philosophy, ethics, culture—and the room votes on which to use for each round. This means you can't over-prepare for one narrow subject. You need broad readiness and the ability to construct arguments quickly on unfamiliar ground.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                No shouting. Victory goes to the strongest case.
            </blockquote>
            <cite>SuperDebate's core principle</cite>
        </div>

