        <h2>THE EVENT EXPERIENCE</h2>

        <p>
            Knowing what to expect removes anxiety. Here's how a SuperDebate evening typically unfolds.
        </p>

        <h3>Before the First Round</h3>

        <p>
            Arrive early. Use the buffer to settle in, find your materials, read the room. Watch how people interact. Notice who seems experienced, who seems nervous, who seems aggressive. You're not scheming—you're orienting. The Greeks called this reading the <em>kairos</em>: the situation's texture.
        </p>

        <p>
            Topic submission happens at the start. Have two or three ideas ready—questions you'd genuinely enjoy debating. "Should AI development be paused?" "Is economic growth compatible with environmental sustainability?" "Do we have moral obligations to future generations?" Good topics have reasonable positions on both sides; they're not gotchas designed to embarrass one view.
        </p>

        <p>
            When the room votes, pay attention to what wins. This tells you what this particular group cares about—useful intelligence for calibrating your arguments throughout the evening.
        </p>

        <h3>During Rounds</h3>

        <p>
            Each round, you'll face a new configuration: new topic, new opponent (or partner), new side assignment. This rotation is deliberate. It prevents any single bad matchup from ruining your night. It also means you might argue against a position you defended an hour ago. Good. That's how you learn what you actually believe versus what you can merely argue.
        </p>

        <p>
            The specific timing varies by format. The <a href="/superdebate-format/">Format Guide</a> details the full 28-minute structure with constructives, cross-examination, and rebuttals. But you might also encounter shorter rounds—quick-fire exchanges designed for agility rather than depth. Adapt. The skills transfer; only the time pressure changes.
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Format Check</div>
            <p>Before each round begins, confirm the structure:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>How long is each speech?</li>
                <li>Is there cross-examination?</li>
                <li>How much prep time, if any?</li>
                <li>Who speaks first?</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Don't assume. Different rounds might run different formats. Thirty seconds of clarification prevents three minutes of confusion.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Community Judging</h3>

        <p>
            Spectators and non-competitors help judge each round. This is unusual if you're used to expert panels, but it reflects SuperDebate's democratic ethos. The audience isn't passive—they're participants in determining who argued better.
        </p>

        <p>
            What this means for you: don't pitch only to debate experts. The person scoring your round might be a first-timer who wandered in curious. Clarity beats jargon. Accessible examples beat insider references. The <a href="/chapters/part-2/chapter-05-ethos/">ethos you built</a> by being understandable serves you here.
        </p>

        <p>
            Judges use simple, fair criteria. They're not looking for technical debate tricks—they're looking for who made the better argument. Sound reasoning, credible evidence, responsive engagement. The fundamentals from this book.
        </p>

        <h3>Group Reflection</h3>

        <p>
            Events end with reflection—participants share insights, lessons, and standout arguments from the evening. This isn't filler. It's where learning consolidates. You hear what others noticed. You discover that the argument you thought won actually fell flat for half the room. You find out your opponent learned something from you.
        </p>

        <p>
            Participate honestly. Share what surprised you. Acknowledge good arguments from opponents. This is where reputation compounds—people remember who was gracious in reflection, not just who won rounds.
        </p>

