        <h2>SOLO VS. TEAM DEBATE</h2>

        <p>
            The choice between debating solo or with a partner isn't just logistical—it changes how you think.
        </p>

        <h3>Solo Debate</h3>

        <p>
            Everything is yours. Every speech, every question, every decision. The upside: complete control, no coordination overhead, no partner who misunderstands your strategy. The downside: no one to catch what you miss, no backup when your mind blanks, no second perspective on a tricky argument.
        </p>

        <p>
            Solo rewards preparation and composure. You need your case structure internalized deeply enough to deliver it while simultaneously planning your cross-examination questions. You need recovery skills for when things go wrong—because there's no teammate to cover while you collect yourself.
        </p>

        <p>
            The Greeks who competed in individual athletic events trained alone. They developed self-reliance and self-knowledge. Solo debate builds the same qualities.
        </p>

        <h3>Team Debate</h3>

        <p>
            With a partner, you divide responsibilities—but you also multiply potential failure modes. Coordination errors kill teams that would win as individuals. If you take constructive and your partner takes rebuttals, you need shared understanding of the case. Nothing worse than your partner "defending" your argument by accidentally contradicting it.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Before the round:</strong> Agree on case structure, key evidence, and fallback positions. Agree on signals—a word or gesture that means "I've got this" or "help me out." Agree on who answers what in cross-ex.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>During the round:</strong> Take notes for your partner. If they're speaking, you're flowing. Slide them a note with the key point they should hit. Cover their gaps without undermining their credibility.
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Partner Debrief</div>
            <p>Between rounds, spend two minutes with your partner:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>What worked?</li>
                <li>What didn't?</li>
                <li>What will we do differently next round?</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Don't skip this. Teams that debrief improve; teams that don't repeat mistakes. Keep it short, keep it constructive, keep it forward-looking.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
            Team debate rewards complementary skills. If you're strong on cross-examination and your partner excels at big-picture synthesis, divide accordingly. Play to strengths. The goal isn't fairness in workload—it's winning the round.
        </p>

