        <h2>ADAPTING TO MODULAR FORMATS</h2>

        <p>
            SuperDebate's flexibility means you can't memorize one approach. The 28-minute format has specific phases, but you might face 15-minute rounds, or rapid-fire 5-minute exchanges, or formats you've never seen before. Adaptability is the skill.
        </p>

        <h3>When Time Shrinks</h3>

        <p>
            Shorter formats demand compression. You can't develop three contentions with evidence for each—you might have time for one well-supported claim. The prioritization skills from the <a href="/live-response/">Live Response Guide</a> become critical. What's the single most important thing you need to say? Say that.
        </p>

        <p>
            In compressed formats, clash matters more than construction. With limited time to build elaborate cases, the debater who directly engages and refutes wins over the debater who delivers a beautiful but unresponsive speech.
        </p>

        <h3>When Time Expands</h3>

        <p>
            Longer formats reward depth. You can develop nuance, anticipate objections, and extend arguments through multiple layers. But beware the trap: more time doesn't mean more filler. The judge still wants your best arguments, not your complete inventory of every thought you've ever had on the topic.
        </p>

        <p>
            Use extra time for what judges value: stronger evidence, deeper analysis, more thorough engagement with your opponent's best points. Don't use it to repeat yourself or pad with tangents.
        </p>

        <h3>When Structure Changes</h3>

        <p>
            Some rounds might skip cross-examination. Some might have open-format Q&A instead of structured rebuttals. Some might involve the audience directly. Roll with it. The underlying skills—clear thinking, responsive engagement, honest persuasion—transfer across any format.
        </p>

        <p>
            When you encounter an unfamiliar structure, focus on fundamentals: state your position clearly, support it with evidence, address what your opponent actually says, and be the kind of person the judges want to agree with.
        </p>

