        <h2>YOUR FIRST EVENT</h2>

        <p>
            Everyone remembers their first SuperDebate. Usually with a mix of exhilaration and embarrassment. Here's how to maximize the former and minimize the latter.
        </p>

        <h3>Mindset: Learning, Not Winning</h3>

        <p>
            Your first event is reconnaissance. You're gathering data about how club debate actually works—which is different from how you imagine it works. Expect to lose rounds. Expect to feel confused. Expect to make mistakes that seem obvious in retrospect. This is normal. It's called learning.
        </p>

        <p>
            Set a learning goal, not an outcome goal. Not "I want to win three rounds" but "I want to complete every speech without running out of things to say" or "I want to flow my opponent's case accurately." Process goals are achievable and instructive. Outcome goals at your first event set you up for disappointment.
        </p>

        <h3>Managing Nerves</h3>

        <p>
            You will be nervous. Everyone is nervous. The debaters who look confident are just better at hiding it—or they've learned that nervousness and excitement are the same physical sensation, differently labeled. Reframe: you're not scared, you're activated. Your body is giving you energy for the challenge ahead.
        </p>

        <p>
            Physical resets help. Before your first round, find a private moment: ten slow breaths, shoulders back, feet grounded. This isn't woo—it's physiological intervention. Slow breathing activates your parasympathetic nervous system, counteracting the adrenaline spike.
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Pre-Round Reset</div>
            <p>Five minutes before your round:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Materials check:</strong> Paper, pen, timer, water.</li>
                <li><strong>Opening line:</strong> Know exactly how you'll start. Rehearse it mentally.</li>
                <li><strong>Physical reset:</strong> Three deep breaths, unclench your jaw, drop your shoulders.</li>
                <li><strong>Focus outward:</strong> Look at your opponent, the judges, the room. External focus reduces internal spiral.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <h3>What to Bring</h3>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Flowing materials:</strong> Legal pad or dedicated paper, multiple pens (they die at critical moments)</li>
            <li><strong>Timer:</strong> Your phone works, but a dedicated timer is less distracting</li>
            <li><strong>Water:</strong> Dry throat derails speeches</li>
            <li><strong>Snacks:</strong> Three hours is long; hunger destroys focus</li>
            <li><strong>Light notes:</strong> Not scripts, but key facts, quotes, or frameworks you might need</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>After the Event</h3>

        <p>
            Debrief yourself on the way home. What worked? What surprised you? What will you do differently next time? Write it down while it's fresh. These notes are more valuable than any amount of abstract preparation—they're personalized feedback from actual competition.
        </p>

        <p>
            Reach out to people you met. SuperDebate clubs are communities. The person who crushed you in round two might become a practice partner. The nervous newcomer you encouraged might become a regular collaborator. The network matters.
        </p>

