        <h2>BUILDING YOUR REPUTATION</h2>

        <p>
            SuperDebate isn't a one-shot competition. It's a community you return to. Your reputation compounds over time—and reputation is just ethos measured across multiple encounters.
        </p>

        <h3>The Long Game</h3>

        <p>
            Consistency matters more than any single performance. Ten solid debates build more credibility than one brilliant debate followed by nine mediocre ones. Focus on your floor, not your ceiling. Eliminate your worst tendencies before trying to amplify your peak performances.
        </p>

        <p>
            The debates you lose well build more reputation than the debates you win ugly. A pyrrhic victory—achieved through technicalities, aggressive bullying, or bad-faith tactics—might give you one win. But it costs you the goodwill that makes future debates easier. Judges remember. Opponents remember. The community remembers.
        </p>

        <h3>Losing Gracefully</h3>

        <p>
            When your opponent scores a genuine point, acknowledge it. "That's a fair criticism—let me respond directly." When you lose a round, don't make excuses or claim the judges were biased. Say "Good debate, I learned something" and mean it.
        </p>

        <p>
            This isn't weakness—it's wisdom. The <a href="/chapters/part-5/chapter-20-the-philosophers-victory/">philosopher's victory</a> includes learning from defeat. And practically: graciousness in loss is rare enough that people notice. It builds the ethos that helps you win next time.
        </p>

        <div class="featured-quote">
            <blockquote>
                You have not converted a man because you have silenced him.
            </blockquote>
            <cite>John Morley — On Compromise, 1874</cite>
        </div>

        <h3>Community Norms</h3>

        <p>
            Every debate community has its culture. Watch before you assert. Notice what's rewarded—depth of analysis? Aggressive refutation? Collaborative truth-seeking? Notice what's punished—bad faith? Excessive aggression? Evasion? Adapt your style to the venue while keeping your substance.
        </p>

        <p>
            SuperDebate explicitly values reasoned disagreement over rhetorical domination. "No shouting. Victory goes to the strongest case." This frames the community's expectations. You can argue fiercely, but you can't argue meanly. You can disagree completely, but you must engage honestly.
        </p>

        <p>
            Contribute to the community, not just to your win record. Help newcomers feel welcome. Offer to judge when you're not competing. Submit thoughtful topics. Participate fully in reflections. These contributions build social capital that makes the whole experience richer—for you and everyone else.
        </p>

